post_game_survey.1.player.prisoner_strat: I recognized this as the Prisoner's Dilemma and chose Peace as it was the best outcome for both parties. When I saw a pattern emerge, I used it to predict what I thought they would do next.  When I got on top of the second player (when our scores were like 5 to 1), I kept choosing War in order to maintain my advantage.
post_game_survey.1.player.rps_strategy: I tried 10 rounds chosing for myself and attempted to try 10 rounds having the AI chose (I messed up the final choice in that round and chose for myself).  I wanted a large enough sample size to determine if my choses were any better than the AI's.  I did not chose the "ask a friend" option because of two reasons.  First, I didn't think there was an actual human - I thought it was more AI. Second, even if it were a human, I would not have chosen it because I do not know the second person's qualifications and I assumed he/she and I were just as good as the AI.  In the third round, I chose myself as the AI played virtually similarly to me.  I thought I could pick out patterns in the third round and use that to my advantage. I didn't estimate the opposing player would play scissors so many times in a row.  I wonder if the AI would have predicted it.
